To refresh a calendar, you can use JavaScript/jQuery to update the calendar's content dynamically. Here's an example of how you can implement this:

HTML:
```html
<input id="calendar" class="form-control calendarinput rtlinsert" type="text" readonly placeholder="لطفا یک تاریخ ملاقات انتخاب کنید" style="cursor: pointer">
<span class="input-group-addon"><i class="fa fa-calendar" aria-hidden="true"></i></span>
<button id="refreshCalendarBtn" class="btn btn-primary">Refresh Calendar</button>
```

JavaScript:
```javascript
$(document).ready(function() {
  // Initialize calendar using your preferred library (e.g., FullCalendar, jQuery UI DatePicker, etc.)
  // Assuming you are using jQuery UI DatePicker
  $("#calendar").datepicker();

  $("#refreshCalendarBtn").click(function() {
    // Refresh the calendar's content here
    // You can either fetch new data from a server or re-render the existing data
    // For simplicity, let's just reinitialize the calendar
    $("#calendar").datepicker("destroy"); // Destroy the current instance of the calendar
    $("#calendar").datepicker(); // Reinitialize the calendar
  });
});
```

This code adds a button with the id `refreshCalendarBtn` that triggers the calendar refresh when clicked. It assumes you are using jQuery and jQuery UI DatePicker, but you can replace it with any other calendar library if desired.

When the button is clicked, the current instance of the calendar is destroyed using the `destroy` method, and then it is reinitialized to refresh the content.

Make sure to include the necessary JavaScript libraries (e.g., jQuery, jQuery UI) in your HTML file.
